{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514984","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514984"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:29:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12411"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12411"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.78,0.07,0.04,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4919"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106896"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4919"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12411"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"129"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"3583"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8043"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43998"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106896","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106896"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department complaining of double vision. His medical history is significant for chronic headaches and hypertension. Today when he woke up he experienced double vision that improves upon occluding one eye. On examination, he has right upper lid ptosis, mild exotropia and hypotropia. The pupil is round, regular and reactive, however it appears larger than the left eye.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["The ophthalmic division of the trigeminal nerve","Oculomotor nerve","Optic nerve","Trochlear nerve","Abducens nerve"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EClassically, third cranial nerve impairment is associated with a \u201cdown and out\u201d appearance of the ipsilateral eye. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoculomotor (third) cranial nerve \u003C/strong\u003Eplays an important role in the efferent visual system by controlling ipsilateral eye movements, pupil constriction, and upper eyelid elevation.\u00a0Accordingly, damage to the third cranial nerve may cause symptoms of diplopia (due to concurrent hypotropia and exotropia), pupil mydriasis, and upper eyelid ptosis. The presentation is determined by the location of the lesion.\u00a0The clinical manifestations of third cranial nerve dysfunction reflect its constituent parts. Outer parasympathetic fibers supply the ciliary muscles of the eye and the sphincter pupillae (sphincter muscles that cause pupillary constriction).\u00a0The inner somatic fibers of the third cranial nerve supply the levator palpebrae superioris in the eyelid (controlling upper eyelid elevation), and four extraocular muscles that govern ocular motility (the superior, medial, and inferior recti muscles, and the inferior oblique muscle).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe two main aetiologies for third nerve palsy are compression and ischaemia. This patient\u0027s age and history of headache and hypertension raises the suspicion of a compressive aetiology due to an aneurysm in the circle of Willis. Compressive causes (due to a tumour or aneurysm) involve the pupil early on as the parasympathetic fibers travel superficially along the third nerve. Meanwhile, ischaemic causes (secondary to stroke, or microvascular causes like diabetes) may involve pupils later in the course of the disease or may spare the pupil all together.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to distinguish compressive and ischaemic causes in a patient presenting with third nerve palsy as the management varies widely. Compressive causes require urgent neuroimaging with MRI and possible neurosurgical intervention. On the other hand, ischaemic causes like diabetes in the absence of focal neurological defect may be observed for spontaneous resolution and optimization of cardiovascular risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other nerves listed do not cause ptosis and pupil dilation. \u003Cstrong\u003EFourth nerve palsy or superior oblique palsy \u003C/strong\u003Ecan cause misalignment of the eyes and can affect one or both eyes. \u003Cstrong\u003ESixth nerve palsy or abducens palsy \u003C/strong\u003Ecan cause the eye to cross inward toward the nose. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eophthalmic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is a part of the corneal reflex, and together with the facial nerve, the palpebral reflex. When the ophthalmic nerve is damaged, there is a lack of these reflexes. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eoptic nerve\u003C/strong\u003E is the nerve that connects and transmits information between the eye and the brain. Optic nerve damage can lead to vision distortion, vision loss, and blindness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Third nerve palsy causes total or partial ptosis with deviation of the eye outward and downward. Pupil may be involved where the pupil appears larger than the other eye with sluggish or normal reaction to light.","Compressive third nerve palsy often involves the pupil early due to superficial parasympathetic fibers, requiring urgent neuroimaging.","Ischaemic third nerve palsy may spare the pupil and often resolves spontaneously with risk factor management."],"references":["Singh RB, Shergill S, Singh KP, Thakur S. Down and out: acquired oculomotor nerve palsy. BMJ Case Rep. 2019 Aug 21;12(8):e231485. doi: 10.1136/bcr-2019-231485. PMID: 31439563; PMCID: PMC6720649. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC6720649/","Sadagopan KA, Wasserman BN. Managing the patient with oculomotor nerve palsy. Curr Opin Ophthalmol. 2013 Sep;24(5):438-47. doi: 10.1097/ICU.0b013e3283645a9b. PMID: 23872817. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23872817/","Kook DB, Park BH, Hwang E, Kim CH. Traumatic oculomotor nerve palsy. Arch Plast Surg. 2015 Mar;42(2):250-2. doi: 10.5999/aps.2015.42.2.250. Epub 2015 Mar 16. PMID: 25798404; PMCID: PMC4366714. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4366714/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12411"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T00:10:24+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T00:10:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4919"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106896"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09: